The lime had nearly exhausted, when on the last day of the year, one of his guardians entered his room, began to converse with his physician on the melancholy circumstance of Avbrcy's being in such a state, when his sister was going next day to be married. Instantly he turned to see who was there. Glad of this mark of returning intellect, of which they feared he had been deprived, they mentioned the name of the Earl of Marsden Thinking that this was a young Earl whom he had met with in society, Aubrey seemed pleased, and astonished them still more by his intention to be present at the nuptials, and desiring to see his sister. They answered not, but in a few minutes his father was with him. He was apparently again affected by the influence of her lovely smile; for he pressed her to his breast, and kissed her cheek, with tears, flying from the thought of his brother being once more alive to the feelings of affection. He began to speak with all his wonted warmth, and to congratulate her upon her marriage with a person so distinguished for rank and every accomplishment; when he suddenly perceived a locket upon her breast; opening it, what was his surprise at beholding the features of the monster who had so long influenced his life. He seized the portrait in a paroxysm of rage, and trampled it underfoot. Upon her asking him why he thus destroyed the resemblance of her future busbarid, he looked as if he did not understand her;
then seizing her hands and gazing on her with a startled expression of concern, he bade her swear that she would never wed this monster, for he;
but he could not advance—it seemed as if that voice again bade her remember his oath—he turned suddenly round, thinking Lord Ruthuen was near him but saw no one. In the meantime, the guardians and physican, who had heard the whole, thought this could be a return of his disorder; and so soliciting him from Miss Aubrey, desired him to leave him. He fell upon his knees to them, he implored, begged of them to deign. They attempted to justify to himself that the injustice he imagined had taken possession of his mind, endeavored to pacify him, and reconciled.
